{"author":"Joe Oakhart","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Context\n\nFills the **T2 semantic-resolution tier** deferred out of the code-grounding v1 floor (epic\n`8f6c-6008-33f3-4f82`, closed). v1 shipped the deterministic, polyglot, fail-open **T0\n(manifest/registry existence) + T1 (ctags/tree-sitter syntactic)** floor plus a **T2\nabstain-by-default seam**: `TIER_T2` exists in the closed tier vocabulary but is never emitted, and\nmember/dotted references abstain inline in `resolve.refute_absence` (tagged \"member binding is T2\").\nThis epic wires a real, self-contained, opt-in T2 backend behind that seam **without changing the\nthree-valued evidence contract (`refuted` / `match` / `abstain`) or its consumers**.\n\nConstraints any T2 backend must respect (why T2 was deferred):\n- **Not deterministic by nature.** Semantic resolution is a function of machine state (installed deps,\n  build state, runtime versions), not just the artifact. Every failure mode\n  (not-installed / not-built / wrong-version / hung) is indistinguishable from a genuinely fake symbol.\n- **Confirm-only verdict asymmetry.** A T2 `refuted` (an asserted absence disproved — the reference\n  resolves) is trustworthy; an asserted absence is suspect unless the environment is known-good. So\n  T2 emits a trustworthy `refuted` and otherwise **`abstain`s** (the canonical outcome for\n  \"unknown\") — it never sits on a deterministic blocking path.\n- **Cannot be borrowed from the ambient environment.** No reliance on an externally-configured MCP\n  server (e.g. Serena) or a host toolchain; the backend is self-contained + opt-in.\n\n> **Terminology (locked to the code vocabulary).** The three-valued outcome is\n> `OUTCOME_REFUTED=\"refuted\"` / `OUTCOME_MATCH=\"match\"` / `OUTCOME_ABSTAIN=\"abstain\"` (`evidence.py`).\n> \"present\" is the informal gloss for `refuted` (absence disproved); \"unknown\" is the informal gloss\n> for `abstain`. This epic writes `refuted` / `abstain` everywhere; the glosses appear only in prose.\n\n## Decided v1 design\n\n**Selected v1 backend: one-shot compiler/checker-CLI diagnostics** (candidate 2), starting with\n`pyright --outputjson` for Python. Rationale over the alternatives: no long-lived server (simplest to\nfail-open + batch), no ambient dependency (the checker is an opt-in extra / PATH probe), and it yields\na trustworthy `refuted` when the checker runs cleanly. The **bundled LSP-client library** (candidate\n1) and **containerized/hermetic** (candidate 3) tiers are **deferred** — the LSP path multiplies the\nper-language server/runtime/config surface; the containerized path's gating cost is an egress-locked\nsingle-tenant microVM sandbox (arbitrary-code-execution on untrusted client repos). Both remain future\nbackends behind the same seam this epic establishes.\n\n## Design specifics (resolving the plan-review indeterminates)\n\n**The seam is a dispatch function, not a plugin registry (Rule-of-Three).** With one concrete backend\nshipping, a general `T2Backend` Protocol + registry is speculative abstraction. S2 instead adds one\nmodule `src/rebar/grounding/semantic.py` exposing:\n\n```python\ndef refute_semantic(reference, *, repo_root, config, timeout=None) -> dict | None\ndef available_backends() -> list[dict]   # [{name, available, version}] for grounding_info, fail-open\nT2_BACKENDS: tuple[str, ...] = (\"pyright\",)   # the closed set of selectable backend names\n```\n\n`refute_semantic` returns a **normalized T2 evidence record** (`refuted@T2` or `abstain@T2`) or\n**`None`** meaning \"T2 declined to run — fall back to the caller's T1 record\" (default-off path). A\nfuture backend adds a name to `T2_BACKENDS` and a branch in `refute_semantic` — no premature Protocol.\n\n**Escalation call-site (single owner): `oracle.refute_absence`.** After the T1/deps lanes return,\nif the record is an `abstain` on a `member`/dotted reference or a not-found bare `symbol`/`import`,\n`oracle.refute_absence` calls `semantic.refute_semantic(...)`; a returned `refuted@T2` replaces the\nT1 abstain, otherwise the T1 record is returned unchanged. `resolve.refute_absence` (the standalone\nT1 lane) is **not** modified — keeping T2 out of the T1 lane preserves T1's determinism.\n\n**Config schema** (`.rebar/grounding.toml`, `[grounding]`, read by `resolve.load_config`; default-off):\n- `t2_enabled` : bool, default `false` — the master opt-in.\n- `t2_backend` : string in `T2_BACKENDS`, default `\"pyright\"` — an unknown value fails open to\n  disabled (abstain), never a raise.\n- `t2_timeout_seconds` : number, default `30` — the bounded per-invocation subprocess timeout.\n\n**`grounding_info` change is explicit code, not free.** `oracle._backend_availability()` is a\nhardcoded list today; S2 appends `*semantic.available_backends()` to it. The `grounding_info` schema's\n`backends[]` name field is an open string, so a new backend name validates without a schema change\n(S2 adds a conformance assertion proving this).\n\n**pyright invocation model (the trustworthiness crux).** pyright is invoked **over the project root**\n(not single-file) via the fail-open `harness.run_tool` with `t2_timeout_seconds`, so cross-module\nimports resolve. The confirm-only decision for a reference in file F:\n- **`refuted@T2`** iff: pyright ran and produced parseable JSON, **AND** F has **zero**\n  import-resolution diagnostics (`reportMissingImports` / `reportMissingModuleSource` — the\n  \"environment built\" precondition), **AND** there is **no** diagnostic at the reference's\n  span/name (`reportAttributeAccessIssue` / `reportUndefinedVariable` / unresolved-import).\n- **`abstain@T2`** (closed reason) in every other case: tool absent (`no_tool`), non-Python\n  reference (`unsupported_lang`), no locatable file (`ambiguous`), unparseable output\n  (`parse_error`), timeout (`timeout`), crash (`other`), F has unresolved imports so the env is\n  not-built (`other`, detail records it), or a diagnostic sits at the reference (`other` — a\n  suspected-absent is never asserted). One pyright run per review is cached by project root and\n  reused across references (no per-reference re-invocation).\n\nIf real pyright output does not cleanly partition these diagnostic codes, the backend **abstains**\n(fail-safe): S3's tests pin the mapping against captured real `--outputjson` fixtures, and any\nunmapped/ambiguous code routes to `abstain`, never `refuted`.\n\n## Related: IaC grounding lane — split out\n\nThe Terraform `validate`/Registry/`plan` tiering is a distinct domain (not a code-build environment)\n— it becomes its **own sibling epic** (created by S1, linked `relates_to`), not a child here.\n\n## Decomposition (3 stacked children, bottom → top; landed as one Gerrit feature branch)\n\n- **S1 — ADR + IaC split (design/doc):** an ADR under `docs/adr/` recording the backend selection,\n  the confirm-only mapping, the minimal-seam (no-registry) decision, and the deferral of\n  LSP-lib/containerized; plus creation of the sibling IaC epic.\n- **S2 — T2 seam (default-off):** `semantic.py` (`refute_semantic` / `available_backends` /\n  `T2_BACKENDS`), the three config keys, escalation in `oracle.refute_absence`, and\n  `_backend_availability()` reporting — all default-off so behavior is byte-identical when\n  `t2_enabled=false`, proven by a regression test.\n- **S3 — pyright diagnostics backend:** the Python backend `refute_semantic` dispatches to, the\n  optional `grounding-t2` extra, docs (`docs/grounding.md` T2 section + config keys), and a\n  per-backend fail-open matrix pinned against real pyright `--outputjson` fixtures.\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n- One self-contained, opt-in T2 backend (pyright) implements the v1 seam and emits `TIER_T2` evidence\n  records that validate against `grounding.schema.json`, with zero edits to the evidence contract or\n  its consumers (`5fd2` DET floor, `9da1` reviewers).\n- Every T2 outcome is `refuted` (trustworthy) or `abstain` (a closed structured reason); no code path\n  emits an asserted absence.\n- With `t2_enabled=false` (the default) the full grounding test suite is byte-identical to pre-epic\n  behavior (regression test proves it); T2 never appears on a deterministic blocking path.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] S1 lands an ADR under `docs/adr/` that names the v1 backend (pyright compiler-CLI diagnostics),\n      records the confirm-only mapping and the minimal-seam decision, and creates + links a sibling\n      IaC epic; the LSP-lib and containerized tiers are recorded as deferred with their tradeoffs.\n- [ ] S2 lands `semantic.refute_semantic`/`available_backends`/`T2_BACKENDS`, the three\n      `.rebar/grounding.toml` keys, the `oracle.refute_absence` escalation, and the\n      `_backend_availability()` reporting — with `t2_enabled=false` producing byte-identical evidence\n      to pre-epic behavior, proven by a default-off regression test in `tests/unit/grounding/`.\n- [ ] S3 lands the pyright backend that emits `refuted@T2` when pyright runs, the file has zero\n      import-resolution diagnostics, and there is no diagnostic at the reference; and emits\n      `abstain@T2` with a closed reason for tool-absent / non-Python / no-file / parse-error /\n      timeout / crash / env-not-built / diagnostic-at-reference.\n- [ ] No code path emits an asserted absence: verified by a test asserting `refute_semantic` returns\n      only `refuted` or `abstain` outcomes across the fail-open matrix.\n- [ ] Self-contained + opt-in: the backend is gated behind the `grounding-t2` optional extra plus\n      `t2_enabled`, and returns `abstain(no_tool)` (never a raise) when pyright is absent — proven by\n      a test that runs with pyright off `PATH`.\n- [ ] Fail-open matrix passes for the pyright backend (unsupported lang / no tool / no locatable file\n      / crash / timeout / diagnostic-present / env-not-built → `abstain`), pinned against captured\n      real `pyright --outputjson` fixtures.\n- [ ] `grounding_info` (CLI `grounding-info`, MCP `grounding_info`, library `rebar.grounding_info()`)\n      lists the pyright T2 backend with its detected availability/version, and the output still\n      validates against `grounding_info.schema.json`.\n- [ ] Proving command green: `pytest tests/unit/grounding/ && make lint` passes; all three children\n      (S1–S3) closed and landed on `main` via the Gerrit feature branch.\n\n## Planned file impact\n\n- `docs/adr/00NN-code-grounding-t2-semantic-resolution.md` (S1, new ADR)\n- `src/rebar/grounding/semantic.py` (S2, new T2 dispatch seam)\n- `src/rebar/grounding/resolve.py` (S2, `GroundingConfig` + `load_config` T2 keys)\n- `src/rebar/grounding/oracle.py` (S2, escalation + `_backend_availability`)\n- `src/rebar/grounding/pyright_backend.py` (S3, the pyright backend)\n- `pyproject.toml` (S3, `grounding-t2` optional extra)\n- `docs/grounding.md` (S3, T2 section + config keys)\n- `tests/unit/grounding/` (S2 regression + S3 fail-open matrix)"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783124474688397001,"uuid":"fa3ebf23-e711-401d-adb7-522abe159d10"}